<div class="mb-requirement-container">
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-14125">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> </span>
      <b>NOTE: </b> The official merit badge pamphlets are now free and
      downloadable
      <a
        href="https://filestore.scouting.org/filestore/Merit_Badge_ReqandRes/Pamphlets/Metalwork.pdf"
        target="_blank"
        >HERE</a
      >
      or can be purchased at the
      <a href="https://www.scoutshop.org/" target="_blank ">Scout Shop.</a>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13583">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 1. </span>
      Read the safety rules for metalwork. Discuss how to be safe while working
      with metal. Discuss with your counselor the additional safety rules that
      apply to the metalwork option you choose for requirement 5. <br /><i
        >Resource:</i
      >
      <a href="https://youtu.be/OsPSSayWEOU" target="_blank"
        >Metalwork Tools Workshop Safety Training (video)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13542">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 2. </span>
      Explain the following terms: native metal, malleable, metallurgy, alloy,
      nonferrous, and ferrous. Then do the following: <br /><i>Resource:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/Q5t4D_4DwS0" target="_blank"
        >Metallurgy: From Rocks to Alloys (video)</a
      >
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13542 mb-requirement-id-13543">
        (a) Name two nonferrous alloys used by pre-Iron Age metalworkers. Name
        the metals that are combined to form these alloys. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/_5iNPCCeZb0" target="_blank"
          >How Alloys Made the Bronze Age Possible. Forging a New Era (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/sGb28SC4ZjY" target="_blank"
          >From Gold and Silver to Electrum: The Truth About This Rare Alloy
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13542 mb-requirement-id-13544">
        (b) Name three ferrous alloys used by modern metalworkers. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/s6dh0ml-KHY" target="_blank"
          >What Are the Different Types of Steel? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13542 mb-requirement-id-13545">
        (c) Describe how to work-harden a metal. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/iH7OJKreTx0" target="_blank"
          >Work Hardening and Annealing (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/xuL2yT-B2TM" target="_blank"
          >Self Organising Steel Balls Explain Metal Heat Treatment (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13542 mb-requirement-id-13546">
        (d) Describe how to anneal a nonferrous and a ferrous metal. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/YLMq8lCml3c" target="_blank"
          >Annealing Stainless Steel Spoons (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/8Pb7KP1t4i8" target="_blank"
          >Introduction to Annealing (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/DPa4LmO7L1s" target="_blank"
          >How to Anneal Silver, Copper and Other Nonferrous Metals (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13547">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 3. </span>
      Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13547 mb-requirement-id-13548">
        (a) Work-harden a piece of 26- or 28-gauge sheet brass or sheet copper.
        Put a 45-degree bend in the metal, then heavily peen the area along the
        bend line to work-harden it. Note the amount of effort that is required
        to overcome the yield point in this unworked piece of metal. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/Bau_opy5du4" target="_blank"
          >Work Hardening of Copper (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13547 mb-requirement-id-13549">
        (b) Soften the work-hardened piece from requirement 3(a) by annealing
        it, and then try to remove the 45-degree bend. Note the amount of effort
        that is required to overcome the yield point.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13547 mb-requirement-id-13550">
        (c) Make a temper color index from a flat piece of steel. Using hand
        tools, make and temper a center punch of medium-carbon or high-carbon
        steel. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/loewH904oOk" target="_blank"
          >How to Forge a Center Punch (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13584">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 4. </span>
      Do ONE of the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13584 mb-requirement-id-13585">
        (a) Identify three career opportunities that would use skills and
        knowledge in metalworking. Pick one and research the training,
        education, certification requirements, experience, and expenses
        associated with entering the field. Research the prospects for
        employment, starting salary, advancement opportunities and career goals
        associated with this career. Discuss what you learned with your
        counselor and whether you might be interested in this career. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/t3cAgVHqHlw" target="_blank"
          >Sheet Metal Workers Career Video (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/WGaOFcQVLXo" target="_blank"
          >What Kinds of Careers Are in Metalcasting? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/FJfR-oLE76k" target="_blank"
          >Blacksmithing 101: What is Blacksmithing? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/t9tQ1-wCUBw" target="_blank"
          >Career Advice on Becoming a Silversmith (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13584 mb-requirement-id-13586">
        (b) Identify how you might use the skills and knowledge in metalworking
        to pursue a personal hobby. Research the additional training required,
        expenses, and affiliation with organizations that would help you
        maximize the enjoyment and benefit you might gain from it. Discuss what
        you learned with your counselor and share what short-term and long-term
        goals you might have if you pursued this. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/SUqdthgh3Uw" target="_blank"
          >Why Blacksmithing? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/6TshB-Zemno" target="_blank"
          >The Lost Art of Tinsmithing (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtube.com/shorts/nr8BpATBXKk" target="_blank"
          >Working with Silver is Awesome (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-13551">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 5. </span>
      After completing the first four requirements, complete ONE of the
      following options:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13551 mb-requirement-id-13552">
        <strong>Option A—Sheet Metal Mechanic/Tinsmith.</strong> Do ALL of the
        following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13552 mb-requirement-id-13556">
        (1) Name and describe the use of the basic sheet metalworking tools.
        <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/I6Sliu42IJw" target="_blank"
          >Essential Metal Fabrication Tools for Beginners: Tips and How I Use
          Them! (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13552 mb-requirement-id-13557">
        (2) Create a sketch of two objects to make from sheet metal. Include
        each component's dimensions on your sketch, which need not be to scale.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13552 mb-requirement-id-13553">
        (3) Make two objects out of 24- or 26-gauge sheet metal. Use patterns
        either provided by your counselor or made by you and approved by your
        counselor. Construct these objects using a metal that is appropriate to
        the object's ultimate purpose, and using cutting, bending, edging, and
        either soldering or brazing. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/XtiYADl3PEo" target="_blank"
          >How To Make a Sheet Metal Box (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13553 mb-requirement-id-13554">
        (a) One object also must include at least one riveted component.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13553 mb-requirement-id-13555">
        (b) If you do not make your objects from zinc-plated sheet steel or
        tin-plated sheet steel, preserve your work from oxidation. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/_-Gfwzc5ASE" target="_blank"
          >How To Prevent Rust (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13551 mb-requirement-id-13558">
        <strong>Option B—Silversmith.</strong> Do ALL of the following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13558 mb-requirement-id-13563">
        (1) Name and describe the use of a silversmith's basic tools. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/vRd5YcRpyig" target="_blank"
          >Silversmithing Tools for Beginners | All You Need to get Started
          Making Jewelry! (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13558 mb-requirement-id-13564">
        (2) Create a sketch of two objects to make from sheet silver. Include
        each component's dimensions on your sketch, which need not be to scale.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13558 mb-requirement-id-13559">
        (3) Make two objects out of 18- or 20-gauge sheet copper. Use patterns
        either provided by your counselor or made by you and approved by your
        counselor. Both objects must include a soldered joint. If you have prior
        silversmithing experience, you may substitute sterling silver, nickel
        silver, or lead-free pewter. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/Q_gejiVEClE" target="_blank"
          >The Basics of Soldering | Jewelry 101 (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13559 mb-requirement-id-13560">
        (a) At least one object must include a sawed component you have made
        yourself. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/KfA9HlzyAHU" target="_blank"
          >Step-by-Step Guide to Sawing for Handmade Jewelry (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13559 mb-requirement-id-13561">
        (b) At least one object must include a sunken part you have made
        yourself. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/_kGPPtUYuI4" target="_blank"
          >Basic Sinking &amp; Planishing (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13559 mb-requirement-id-13562">
        (c) Clean and polish your objects. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/A-NTbRUhASQ" target="_blank"
          >How I Clean &amp; Polish Jewelry RIGHT After Casting | Step By Step
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13551 mb-requirement-id-13565">
        <strong>Option C—Founder.</strong> Do ALL of the following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13565 mb-requirement-id-13569">
        (1) Name and describe the use of the basic parts of a two-piece mold.
        Name at least three different types of molds. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/VveT7Ve7IeQ" target="_blank"
          >What Are the Common Types of Metal Casting Process in Engineering and
          Industry (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13565 mb-requirement-id-13570">
        (2) Create a sketch of two objects to cast in metal. Include each
        component's dimensions on your sketch, which need not be to scale.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13565 mb-requirement-id-13566">
        (3) Make two molds, one using a pattern provided by your counselor and
        another one you have made yourself that has been approved by your
        counselor. Position the pouring gate and vents yourself. <br /><br /><b
          >Note:</b
        >
        Do not use copyrighted materials as patterns. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/XlRK_SMWX7Y" target="_blank"
          >Sand Casting Lesson for Beginners - Step-by-Step (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13566 mb-requirement-id-13567">
        (a) Using lead-free pewter, make a casting using a mold provided by your
        counselor.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13566 mb-requirement-id-13568">
        (b) Using lead-free pewter, make a casting using the mold that you have
        made.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13551 mb-requirement-id-13571">
        (d) <strong>Option D—Blacksmith.</strong> Do ALL of the following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13571 mb-requirement-id-13581">
        (1) Name and describe the use of a blacksmith's basic tools. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/dw3rSK7L1Aw?si=DGyYJl6q65MdrVNY"
          target="_blank"
          >Basic Blacksmithing Tools (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13571 mb-requirement-id-13582">
        (2) Make a sketch of two objects to hot-forge. Include each component's
        dimensions on your sketch, which need not be to scale.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13571 mb-requirement-id-13572">
        (3) Using low-carbon steel at least 1/4 inch thick, perform the
        following exercises:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13572 mb-requirement-id-13573">
        (a) Draw out by forging a taper. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/xUPM9emeOZU?si=s3kZQxvw4G2aXI3u"
          target="_blank"
          >Blacksmith Basics: How to Draw Out a Taper (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/U363Q8UxrJA" target="_blank"
          >Tapering for Beginners (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13572 mb-requirement-id-13574">
        (b) Use the horn of the anvil by forging a <strong>U</strong>-shaped
        bend. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/-ESejG0pcGs?si=tmuAxFac5Ki45E-D"
          target="_blank"
          >Blacksmithing For Beginners - Working On The Horn Of The Anvil
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13572 mb-requirement-id-13575">
        (c) Form a decorative twist in a piece of square steel. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/PINugkxOues?si=XuDneyIAtlTuzb78"
          target="_blank"
          >Blacksmithing for Beginners - Twisting Bar Stock (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13572 mb-requirement-id-13576">
        (d) Use the edge of the anvil to bend metal by forging an
        <strong>L</strong>-shaped bend. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/Rudy5ZNGp1A?si=p_11xuWq6tk_Nq6M"
          target="_blank"
          >Fundamentals of Blacksmithing - Bending (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13571 mb-requirement-id-13577">
        (4) Using low-carbon steel at least 1/4 inch thick, make the two objects
        you sketched that require hot-forging. Be sure you have your counselor's
        approval before you begin.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13577 mb-requirement-id-13578">
        (a) Include a decorative twist on one object. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/PINugkxOues?si=XuDneyIAtlTuzb78"
          target="_blank"
          >Blacksmithing for Beginners - Twisting Bar Stock (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13577 mb-requirement-id-13579">
        (b) Include a hammer-riveted joint in one object. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtube.com/shorts/A73-0yq-XKQ?si=KfdUqcsa5E1Q-NBS"
          target="_blank"
          >Forging Red Hot Rivet on This Awesome Anvil (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-13577 mb-requirement-id-13580">
        (c) Preserve your work from oxidation. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/xIvjVN7bk5w?si=QWPSQ_-ghLJ1hi45"
          target="_blank"
          >Preventing Rust The Old Fashioned Way And Protecting Some Gifts
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
</div>
